    <text>
        <front>
            <div type="summary">
                <p>
                    In this letter to Leonard Woolf, Edward Thompson agrees to an American edition of his book, noting concerns about potential misuse of the content by anti-British groups in the U.S. He wants it printed to secure copyright and expose British foreign office influence on missions.
                </p>
            </div>
        </front>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <address>
                            <addrLine> SCAR TOP </addrLine>
                            <addrLine> BOARS HILL, </addrLine>
                            <placeName> OXFORD </placeName> </address>
                        <date when="1926-01-01">
                            1.1.26
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                 
                    <salute>
                        Dear <persName type="recipient">Mr. Woolf,</persName>  
                    </salute>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    Yes, let <persName> Harcourt Bruce </persName> do an American edition, <lb/>
                then. There are so many anti-British circles in the <placeName>U.S.A.</placeName>, esp. <lb/>
                    groups of Bengalis - <persName key="Q7633783">Sudhindra Bose</persName>, <persName key="Q19795189">Basanta Roy</persName>,&amp; Co. - that other- <lb/>
                wise there will certainly be garbled part-printings of the book, <lb/>
                esp. as it is so largely quotation. <lb/>
                </p>
                <p> But I am not content to have it simply anti- <lb/>
                British propaganda, or to feed fat Yankee self-esteem. This <title>Preface</title>  <lb/>
                has cost me a lot of bother, dissatisfied though it leaves me. But  <lb/>
                I shd. like it printed. One small thing that it does is, it saves the  <lb/>
                    American copyright of the book, as printed by  <persName>  Harcourt Bruce </persName>. A  <lb/>
                bigger thing is, it will make a few folk see the way our Foreign  <lb/>
                    Offices have through the <persName key="Q1827237">Lionel Curtises </persName>&amp; <persName>J.R. Motts</persName> collared the  <lb/>
                missions. </p>
            
                <closer>
                    <salute>
                        Yours sincerely
                    </salute>
                    <signed>Edward Thompson</signed>
                    
                    <persName>  Leonard-Woolf Esq. </persName>
                    <address> 
                        <orgName key="Q1623362">The Hogarth Press</orgName> 
                        <placeName>London</placeName>
                    </address>
                    
                    
                </closer>
            </div>
